VALUES
(44, 14, 15, 1, 1, 1, 1, 'which made heaven, and earth', 'Creation and the Living God', 'Both passages emphasize the act of creation, with Acts 14:15 referencing the ''living God'' who made ''heaven, and earth,'' paralleling Genesis 1:1''s declaration of God''s creation of ''the heaven and the earth.'' This connection highlights the foundational belief in God as the creator in both texts.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 15, 24, 14, 22, 22, 'vanities', 'Connection of Vanities and Creation', 'Both passages emphasize the futility of vanities and affirm the sovereignty of God as the creator of all things. Acts 14:15 calls for a turn from vanities to the living God, while Jeremiah 14:22 questions the ability of Gentile vanities to provide rain, acknowledging God as the true creator.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 16, 44, 17, 30, 30, 'suffered all nations to walk in their own ways', 'God''s Response to Ignorance', 'Both passages emphasize God''s previous tolerance of human ignorance. Acts 14:16 notes that God allowed nations to walk in their own ways, while Acts 17:30 indicates a shift where God now commands repentance from this ignorance.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 16, 19, 81, 12, 12, 'walk in their own ways', 'Connection of Human Autonomy', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of allowing nations or people to follow their own ways or desires. Acts 14:16 notes that God permitted nations to walk in their own ways, while Psalms 81:12 reflects God giving people up to their own hearts'' lusts.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 16, 19, 147, 20, 20, 'all nations to walk in their own ways', 'Divine Sovereignty Over Nations', 'This connection highlights God''s unique relationship with nations. Acts 14:16 mentions God''s allowance for nations to walk in their own ways, while Psalms 147:20 emphasizes that He has not dealt so with any nation, indicating a distinction in His judgments.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 16, 45, 1, 28, 28, 'walk in their own ways', 'Divine Allowance and Human Rejection', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s allowance for nations to follow their own ways, which leads to a rejection of divine knowledge. Both passages emphasize the consequences of turning away from God, resulting in a reprobate mind.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 16, 33, 4, 5, 5, 'walk in their own ways', 'Walking in God''s Ways', 'This connection highlights the theme of walking in the ways of one''s chosen deity. Acts 14:16 notes that nations walked in their own ways, while Micah 4:5 contrasts this by emphasizing walking in the name of the Lord.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 16, 45, 1, 21, 25, 'walk in their own ways', 'Divine Allowance and Human Rebellion', 'Both passages emphasize God''s allowance for nations to follow their own ways, leading to a rejection of His glory. This connection highlights the consequences of turning away from God and the resulting moral decline.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 16, 49, 2, 12, 12, 'walk in their own ways', 'God''s Allowance of Alienation', 'This connection highlights the theme of alienation from God. Acts 14:16 speaks of God''s past allowance for nations to walk in their own ways, while Ephesians 2:12 describes being without God and alienated from His promises.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 17, 45, 1, 19, 20, 'he left not himself without witness', 'Divine Witness and Creation', 'Both passages emphasize God''s revelation through creation. Acts 14:17 speaks of God''s goodness and provision, while Romans 1:19-20 highlights how God''s attributes are evident in creation, leaving humanity without excuse.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 17, 29, 2, 23, 23, 'rain from heaven, and fruitful seasons', 'Connection of Rain and Gladness', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of rain as a blessing from God that brings joy and sustenance. Acts 14:17 mentions rain and gladness, while Joel 2:23 speaks of rain and rejoicing in the Lord.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 17, 18, 5, 10, 10, 'rain from heaven', 'Connection of Divine Provision', 'Both passages emphasize God''s role in providing rain, which is essential for fruitful seasons and sustenance. This connection highlights the theme of divine goodness and care for creation.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 17, 5, 11, 14, 14, 'gave us rain from heaven', 'Connection of Divine Provision', 'Both passages emphasize God''s provision of rain, which is essential for fruitful seasons and sustenance. Acts 14:17 highlights God''s goodness through rain, while Deuteronomy 11:14 promises rain for agricultural abundance.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 17, 23, 5, 6, 6, 'rain from heaven', 'Divine Provision and Judgment', 'This connection highlights the contrast between God''s provision of rain and fruitful seasons in Acts 14:17 and the judgment of withholding rain in Isaiah 5:6. Both passages emphasize the significance of rain as a symbol of divine favor or disfavor.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 17, 3, 26, 4, 4, 'rain from heaven, and fruitful seasons', 'Connection of Divine Provision', 'Both passages emphasize God''s provision of rain and fruitful seasons. Acts 14:17 reflects the goodness of God in providing sustenance, paralleling Leviticus 26:4''s promise of rain and agricultural abundance.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 17, 5, 8, 12, 14, NULL, 'Divine Provision and Human Response', 'Both passages emphasize God''s provision for humanity, highlighting the blessings of food and abundance. They also warn against forgetting the Lord in times of prosperity.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 18, 24, 44, 16, 17, NULL, 'Rejection of Divine Instruction', 'This connection highlights the people''s refusal to heed divine warnings in both passages. In Acts, the people nearly worship Paul and Barnabas, while in Jeremiah, the people reject the prophet''s message in favor of their own desires.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 18, 1, 11, 6, 6, 'not done sacrifice unto them', 'Unity and Restraint in Actions', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of restraint in the context of collective human action. In Acts, the people are nearly restrained from making sacrifices, while in Genesis, God notes that nothing will be restrained from the unified peopleâ€™s ambitions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 18, 1, 19, 9, 9, NULL, 'Rejection of Divine Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of people rejecting divine authority. In both passages, the individuals involved resist the guidance and judgment of those sent by God, leading to conflict and potential harm.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 18, 2, 32, 21, 23, 'sacrifice unto them', 'Human Response to Divine Authority', 'This connection highlights the people''s tendency to misplace their devotion. In both passages, the people are eager to offer sacrifices or create gods, reflecting a common theme of misguided worship.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 18, 43, 6, 15, 15, 'that they had not done sacrifice', 'Response to Popular Acclamation', 'This connection highlights the theme of public response to figures perceived as powerful. In both passages, there is a reaction from the crowd that seeks to elevate the individuals, whether by sacrifice or by making a king.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 19, 47, 11, 25, 25, 'having stoned Paul', 'Paul''s Suffering and Persecution', 'This connection highlights Paul''s experiences of suffering and persecution. Both passages emphasize the physical violence he endured, specifically mentioning being stoned.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 19, 55, 3, 11, 11, NULL, 'Connection of Persecution Experiences', 'This connection highlights the shared experiences of persecution faced by Paul in both passages. Acts 14:19 describes the stoning of Paul, while 2 Timothy 3:11 references the persecutions endured at the same locations, emphasizing the continuity of his suffering.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 19, 44, 13, 50, 51, 'drew him out of the city', 'Persecution of Paul and Barnabas', 'Both passages emphasize the persecution faced by Paul. In Acts 13:50-51, Paul and Barnabas are expelled from the city, while in Acts 14:19, Paul is stoned, illustrating a continuation of hostility against him.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 19, 44, 14, 5, 5, NULL, 'Connection of Stoning Events', 'Both passages emphasize the act of stoning as a violent response to Paul and his companions. Acts 14:5 mentions a plot to stone them, while Acts 14:19 describes Paul being stoned. This connection highlights the hostility faced by early Christians.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 19, 58, 13, 12, 13, NULL, 'Suffering and Reproach in Christ', 'This connection highlights the theme of suffering for faith. Both passages emphasize enduring reproach, as Paul is stoned and Jesus suffers outside the gate.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 19, 46, 15, 31, 31, NULL, 'Connection of Suffering and Death', 'This connection highlights the theme of suffering and the experience of death in the life of Paul. In Acts, Paul is stoned and presumed dead, while in 1 Corinthians, he speaks of dying daily, reflecting a continual confrontation with death.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 19, 47, 4, 10, 12, NULL, 'Connection of Suffering and Life', 'This connection highlights the theme of suffering for the sake of Jesus and the resulting manifestation of His life. Both passages emphasize the experience of death and dying, leading to the expression of life in believers.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 20, 47, 1, 9, 10, 'rose up', 'Resilience in Deliverance', 'This connection highlights the theme of rising from perilous situations. In Acts, Paul rises after being stoned, while in 2 Corinthians, the focus is on God delivering from death.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 14, 20, 47, 6, 9, 9, NULL, 'Resilience in Adversity', 'This connection highlights the theme of enduring hardship. In Acts 14:20, Paul rises after being stoned, while 2 Corinthians 6:9 speaks of being chastened yet not killed, emphasizing survival despite suffering.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
